# Cyberland ‚Äî ECS systems vs one-shot work

## Principle

Do **not** add an `ISystem` / `IParallelSystem` whose per-frame phase hooks (**`OnEarlyUpdate`**, **`OnFixedUpdate`**, **`OnLateUpdate`**, or parallel equivalents) only perform work that could run **once** (e.g. `IMod.OnLoad`, host init, or a single explicit call after entities exist).

Per-frame registration has a real cost (scheduler walk, virtual dispatch) and obscures intent when nothing about the problem is continuous.

## What belongs in systems

- **Continuous simulation** (movement, timers, AI ticks).
- **Per-frame input sampling** or gameplay that must run in deterministic order with other systems.
- **Work that truly depends on every frame** (e.g. animation advance, particle integration).

**One-time init that still belongs in the scheduler** (not every frame) should use **`ISystem.OnStart`** / **`IParallelSystem.OnStart`**: it runs once when the system entry is first **enabled**, before any **Early** phase callback. Prefer **`IMod.OnLoad`** when no ECS frame ordering is required; use **`OnStart`** when init must run relative to other registered systems. **`SetSystemEnabled(false)`** avoids per-frame cost without unregistering; **`OnStart`** does not run again after re-enable.

## What does not

- **One-time scene setup**: spawn entities, set components from static or load-time data ‚Äî do it in **`IMod.OnLoad`** or a dedicated init helper called from there.
- **Idempotent layout that never changes after load** ‚Äî apply once; do not wrap in a system that repeats the same writes.

## When something is ‚Äúalmost‚Äù one-shot

If you only need to react to **occasional** events (window resize, settings change), prefer:

- Subscribing to an **event** or callback if the engine/host exposes one, or
- A **minimal** system that runs only when a cheap guard detects change (e.g. cached size vs current), **not** a full rewrite of static decor every frame with no delta.

Document **why** a system runs every frame when it is not obvious from the code.
